  "referred_to_by": [
    {
      "type": "LinguisticObject",
      "content": "This is one of the most important fossils in any museum worldwide — the so-called **\"Haarlem Archaeopteryx,\"** described by Teylers' own Collection Manager as **\"the Mona Lisa of the museum's fossil collection.\"** Found in 1855 near Jachenhausen, Bavaria, it was the **chronologically first Archaeopteryx specimen ever discovered** — predating the famous London specimen by six years — but was misidentified as a pterosaur (*Pterodactylus crassipes*) by Hermann von Meyer in 1857. It remained misidentified for over a century until **John Ostrom** recognized feather impressions during a visit to Teylers in September 1970. In **2017**, it was reclassified again: Foth & Rauhut demonstrated it is not *Archaeopteryx* at all, but a new genus — **Ostromia crassipes** — the first anchiornithid dinosaur found outside China. In May 2024, the fossil was secretly transported to the Diamond Light Source synchrotron in the UK for cutting-edge X-ray analysis.",
